column41: Comments
A unique cider bar on a boat, with a sizable outside sitting area and separate bar next to the boat. I fequented this when I lived near King Street but now visits are a lot rarer.

column2: Boyce's Ave, Clifton, Clifton Village, Bristol, BS8 4AA
column41: I have only been here once but what a joyful experience it was, there is even a tractor for decoration.

The number one spot for all things Sports in Bristol. They have a plentitude of Pool tables but unfortunately in recent years have downgraded their number of snooker tables from 4 to 3. This is the best spot to watch live sports unless you are after the national league with three major games already in play.
Unfortunately this is no more, but it used to be a great space to rent out for functions.
Good luck getting a Sunday roast here, they are fully booked each year within minutes. But if you're lucky they may have left over roasties going for free on a Sunday.

column2: 39 Barton Rd, St Philip's, Bristol, BS2 0LF
column41: Incredible pub quiz where my best peformance came when I didn't even enter. They have a lot of local beers and a clear priced menu behind the bar.
Alphabetically the number one spoons in Bristol, some fun architecture here but that doesn't make up for the fact Ben was served a Guinness with no head.
Sometimes feels slightly hidden despite being on the bustling Baldwin Street, maybe because it is just five minutes from King Street.

column2: St Philips Causeway, Arno's Vale, Bristol, BS4 3BD
column41: An interesting pub, potential to be an incredible venue but it is in a supermarket carpark and feels too gimmicky instead of being in an actual castle.

column2: Market Chambers, 20 St Nicholas St, Bristol, BS1 1UB
column41: A nice pub tucked away on St. Nicholas Street with a full horse-shoe bar.
One of the classic half café-half pub lounges in Bristol.

column2: Avon Mill Ln, Keynsham, Bristol, BS31 2UG
column41: A 'car-park pub' it has a nice location, out of the way but entry is dominated by a large car park emphasising how far out of the way this pub is.
Located on the partly-pedrestrianised Cotham Hill Road, this pub doubles, as the same suggests, as a brewery creating some of their own beers. You can even buy kegs of their beer.
Is this too far from a Bridge to call itself a 'Bridge Inn'? There are three different buisnesses between the Bridge and this pub but the limited outdoor seating has views of the Bridge.
Potential to be a great pub, but a very small bar makes long queues a common occurance and paired with a kitchen that seems too small means food often takes a long time to arrive.
A very cosy pub at the bottom of the Christmas Steps with a surprise beer garden in the courtyard behind. This pub has a multi-level bar so they may well have a bigger selection than you think.
More of a restaurant than a pub. Now no more this used to have some very interesting decorations that would not be out of place at a butchers.

column2: Foley Cottage, 129 Hampton Rd, Redland, Bristol, BS6 6JE
column41: This was our post-6-aside Sunday pub, it has everything you'd need from pool tables to Guinness, this has the lot.
The most centrally located Spoons in Bristol, definitely feels like they could add another floor in to increase capacity.

A free darts board, a free Nintendo64, an insane amount of boardgames and a pub quiz that I have been runner up in twice in the last two weeks of writing this. They do Murphy's and Guinness so if you love a stout you'd love this pub. Although there is no food served by the pub they have the menu of a very reasoably priced takeway next door and they'll bring your food to the table in the pub.

column2: Baltic Wharf, Cumberland Rd, Bristol, BS1 6XG
column41: My favourite pub in Bristol, the views up the avon towards the suspension bridge are stunning, the roasts are incredible. This is a nice, warm cozy up in winter and a vibrant yet chill pub in summer.

column2: 10 All Saints Ln, Avon, Bristol, BS1 1JH
column41: Basically the same pub as Mother's Ruin, only with longer opening hours. The pints are usually served in plastics and I believe I have never been here before midnight. A good pub to end a night at.

A Greene King that is very typical of Greene Kings, very centrally located and ideal for a quick pint before (or after) watching a show at the hippodrome, you can rest assured that the pints are significantly cheaper here than at the bar of the hippodrome.
A Corner pub in knowle, the indoor space is small but the bartender told me he was a former Bristol Manor Farm player so a decent chance you'll be able to talk about football.
This pub is hidden away, just around the corner from the Ostrich, it has a rather unique roof-top terrace beer garden which is shadowed by the much taller surrounding buildings.
This always felt more like a food venue than a pub, the food is great and being on a boat is a fun but it can be on the expensive side considering just over the road is the Mardyke.

One of the hardest pub quizzes in Bristol but a very good raffle on a Friday evening redeems this pub, there is always a good selection and has a nice cozy inside. The beer garden doubles as a car park but we'll let that slide since the landlord is a great guy.

column2: 53-55 Sandy Park Rd, Brislington, Bristol, BS4 3PE

Alfred Rd, Windmill Hill, Bristol, BS3 4LU
8 Sandy Park Rd, Brislington, Bristol, BS4 3PE
Clifton Down Station, Whiteladies Rd, Clifton, Bristol, BS8 2PN

column41: We have been here once and got a roast, Good solid options and a great beer garden.
